Examples of 2-D classifications using QDA and KDE methods.¶

In this script, we show the differences in classification performances between the quadratic discriminant analysis (QDA) and the kernel density estimation (KDE) methods.

Both methods are applied to a series of 2-D datasets containing 2 classes with an increasing level spatial complexity.

We estimate the probability distribution function (PDF) of an observation x using a mixture of PDF weighted with their a priori class probabilities $P(C_{i})$:

$P(\bf{x}) = \sum_{i=0}^{N}P(\bf{x}|C_{i}) P(C_{i})$

The two methods differ in the way they compute the $P(\bf{x}|C_{i})$ term.

The QDA method approximates the PDF of each class as a multi-normal gaussian distribution which parameters are adjusted to fit the observations (the datasets).

The KDE method approximates the PDF by convolving the datasets with spatial kernels. Hence, there is no a priori model to guide us; this is a non-parametric model.

Discriminant methods¶

Once the $P(\bf{x}|C_{i})$ values are evaluated, discriminant methods are used to locate the influence zone of each class i over a spatial grid. This corresponds to regions where

$P(\bf{x}|C_{i}) P(C_{i}) > P(\bf{x}|C_{j \ne i}) P(C_{j \ne i})$

or

$h_{i}(\bf{x}) > h_{j \ne i}(\bf{x})$

with the discriminant function $h_{i}(\bf{x})$ defined as

$h_{i}(\bf{x}) = \ln P(\bf{x}|C_{i}) P(C_{i})$

QDA method¶

The discriminant function for the 2-D gaussian PDF is:

$h_{i}(\bf{x}) =\frac{1}{2}\ln |\Sigma_{i}| -\frac{1}{2}(\bf{x}-\bf{\mu_{i}})^\top \Sigma_{i}^{-1} (\bf{x}-\bf{\mu_{i}}) + \ln P(C_{i})$

with

The observation: $\bf{x}=[x_{1} x_{2}]^\top$
The origin: $\bf{\mu_{i}} = [\mu_{1} \mu_{2}]^\top$
The covariance matrix: $\Sigma_{i} = \begin{pmatrix} \sigma_{x_{1}}^2 & \sigma_{x_{1,2}} \\ \sigma_{x_{1,2}} & \sigma_{x_{2}}^2 \end{pmatrix}$

The parameters $\bf{\mu}$ and $\Sigma$ are estimated from the dataset.

KDE method¶

The probability density $P(x|C_{i})$ can be modeled as the convolution of the data distribution with a kernel $K(u)$ designed to smooth the estimated PDF

$P(x|C_{i}) = \large{ \frac{1}{N_{i}h}\sum_{i=1}^{N_{i}} K(\frac{x-x_{i}}{h}) }$

where $N_{i}$ is the number of data points belonging to class i. The level of smoothing is controled by the bandwidth parameter h.

Gaussian and Epanechikov kernels are popular kernels. Their 2-D expressions are:

Gaussian: $K(u)= \frac{1}{2\pi} \exp [-\frac{\|u\|^{2}}{2}]$
Epanechikov: $K(u)= \frac{15}{8\pi}(1-\|u\|^{2})$ for $\|u\| \in [0, 1]$

The discriminant function becomes

$ \begin{align} P(x|C_{i})P(C_{i}) & = \frac{1}{N_{i}h}\sum_{i=1}^{N_{i}} K(\frac{x-x_{i}}{h}) P(C_{i}) \\ & = \frac{1}{Nh}\sum_{i=1}^{N_{i}} K(\frac{x-x_{i}}{h}) \end{align} $

Data normalization¶

Normalize dataset for easier parameter selection for the classification methods.

def normalize_dataset(X, nbins):
    X = StandardScaler().fit_transform(X)
    x_min = 1.1 * X[:,0].min()
    x_max = 1.1 * X[:,0].max()
    y_min = 1.1 * X[:,1].min()
    y_max = 1.1 * X[:,1].max()

    # Generate a spatial grid where the PDF will be evaluated locally.
    xx, yy = np.meshgrid(np.linspace(x_min, x_max, nbins), np.linspace(y_min, y_max, nbins))
    Xgrid = np.c_[xx.ravel(), yy.ravel()]
    
    return (X, Xgrid, xx, yy, x_min, x_max, y_min, y_max)

KDE classification method¶

The KDE method is used to estimate the local probability density function associated to each class. Both PDF and their a priori probabilities are then used to find the local winning class at each point of the grid.

Because the gaussian kernel has an infinite spatial extent, the winning class is defined everywhere. This is not the case with the Epanechikov kernel which drops to zero at distances larger than the bandwidth from any data point. This problem can be alleviated by using larger bandwidths but at the price of losing spatial resolution as we will see in the examples below.

In [3]:
def KDE_classifications(h_gaussian, h_epanechikov, X, y, Xgrid, nbins, prob_C):

    pdf_g = np.zeros((nbins,nbins,2))
    pdf_e = np.zeros((nbins,nbins,2))
    
    kde_g = KernelDensity(bandwidth=h_gaussian, kernel='gaussian', leaf_size=100) 
    kde_e = KernelDensity(bandwidth=h_epanechikov, kernel='epanechnikov', leaf_size=100) 
   
    # Normalisation for each data cluster
    for i in range(2):
        kde_g.fit(X[y == i])  
        Z = np.exp(kde_g.score_samples(Xgrid))
        pdf_g[:,:,i] = Z.reshape([nbins, nbins]) * prob_C[i]

        kde_e.fit(X[y == i])  
        Z = np.exp(kde_e.score_samples(Xgrid))
        pdf_e[:,:,i] =  Z.reshape([nbins, nbins]) * prob_C[i]
        
    # Find winning class
    C_g = np.argmax(pdf_g, axis=2)
    C_e = np.argmax(pdf_e, axis=2)
    
    # Find the zones on the grid where none of the Epanechikov PDF is defined.  
    eps = np.finfo(float).eps
    C_undef = np.logical_and((pdf_e[:,:,0]<eps), (pdf_e[:,:,1]<eps))
    
    # Assign a class 2 to those pixels
    C_e[C_undef] = 2  
    
    return (C_g, C_e)

Classification results displaying function¶

In [4]:
def display_classification_results(C_g, C_e, C_qda, X, y, Xgrid, figName):

    cm_dim = ListedColormap(['#BB0000', '#00BB00', '#000000'])
    cm_bright = ListedColormap(['#FF0000', '#00FF00'])
    
    fig, axs = plt.subplots(1,3, figsize=(15,5), sharex=True, sharey=True) 
    for k in range(3):
        ax = axs.ravel()[k]

        if (k==0):
            # QDA classification results
            ax.pcolormesh(xx, yy, C_qda, cmap=cm_dim, norm=colors.Normalize(0., 2.), zorder=0) 
            ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cm_bright, edgecolors='w')
            ax.set_title('QDA', fontsize=18, color='k')
        elif (k==1):
            # Gaussian KDE classification results            
            ax.pcolormesh(xx, yy, C_g, cmap=cm_dim, norm=colors.Normalize(0., 2.), zorder=0) 
            ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cm_bright, edgecolors='w')
            ax.set_title('KDE (Gaussian Kernel)', fontsize=18, color='k')
        else:
            # Epanechikov KDE classification results    
            # A black color is assigned to zones where the PDF are undefined
            ax.pcolormesh(xx, yy, C_e, cmap=cm_dim, norm=colors.Normalize(0., 2.), zorder=0) 
            ax.scatter(X[:, 0], X[:, 1], c=y, cmap=cm_bright, edgecolors='w')
            ax.set_title('KDE (Epanechikov Kernel)', fontsize=18, color='k')

        ax.set_xlim([x_min,x_max])
        ax.set_ylim([y_min,y_max])
        ax.set_xlabel('$x_{1}$', fontsize=14)
        ax.set_ylabel('$x_{2}$', fontsize=14, rotation=0)
        ax.yaxis.set_label_coords(-0.15, 0.5) 
        ax.grid(None)  
        ax.grid(None)  
    
    fig.tight_layout()
        
    plt.savefig(figName, format='png')

# Number of 2-D points per dataset.
npts = 200

# A priori probability of the clusters
prob_C = np.array([0.5, 0.5]) 

# Number of data points allocated to each cluster 
nc = (npts*prob_C).astype(int)

# Number of spatial bins used in each spatial direction
nbins = 500

# Quadratic discriminant analysis
qda = QuadraticDiscriminantAnalysis(store_covariance=True)

Two isotropic gaussians distributions with identical variance.¶

This is an example where the QDA produces a linear boundary. This is shown in the first panel of the figure below. There is no a priori reason for the KDE method to produce linear boundaries.

Small values of KDE bandwidths were selected to generate noisy boundaries in the next two panels.

The third panel shows a limitation of using the Epanechikov kernel; the PDF associated to a cluster does not extend beyond a bandwidth distance from its outermost data points. The black zones are such regions where no PDF can be computed and thus no winning class can be found.

# QDA classification
C_qda = qda.fit(X, y).predict(Xgrid) 
C_qda = C_qda.reshape(xx.shape)

# KDE classifications
h_gaussian = .01
h_epanechikov = .3

(C_g, C_e) = KDE_classifications(h_gaussian, h_epanechikov, X, y, Xgrid, nbins, prob_C)

# Compare classification results
figName = '2D_KDE_classif_gaussian_1.png'
display_classification_results(C_g, C_e, C_qda, X, y, Xgrid, figName)

What happens when the bandwidths are much larger? In this case, the PDF associated to each cluster is smoothed out and extends beyond the panels' field of view. This creates linear boundaries as can be seen in the figure below. The Epanechikov-resulting PDF are now defined everywhere and the local winning class can be evaluated everywhere; there are no black zones left.

Noisy concentric circles¶

This example shows more complex boundaries. The influence zones of the QDA and the gaussian-KDE are similar.

The Epanechikov-KDE results are very different for the same reason as before; its bandwidth was selected for that reason. Notice how the distance between the black boundaries and the nearest points are equal to the bandwidth, as expected.

Noisy crescents¶

This example shows more complex boundaries. This is a case where the QDA cannot well delineate the influence zones since the boundaries cannot be linear nor quadratic. The gaussian-KDE results are excellent and so are the Epanechikov-KDE results except for the black zones.

Unstructured random distribution¶

This example shows a 2-class distribution with no natural boundary. Once again, this is a case where the QDA method performs poorly since no linear or quadratic boundaries can be found.

The gaussian-KDE results display overfitting to the noisy data. This shows that kernel methods can nevertheless be used to approximate complex distributions since most green and red points are well separated. The spatial resolution is high.

The Epanechikov-KDE results, on the other hand, have a lower spatial resolution. They were obtained using the minimum bandwith value to prevent black zones. The results are less impressive than the previous ones eventhough they showed overfitting. Hence, the limited extent of the Epanechikov kernel has a strong effect on the final spatial resolution.
